[[Major General (United Kingdom)|Major General]] '''Sir Harcourt Mortimer Bengough''' [[Order of the Bath|KCB]] (25 November 1837 <U+2013> 20 March 1922) joined the [[British Army]] in 1855, and retired in 1899, after more than forty years of distinguished service from the [[Crimean War|Crimea]] to all quarters of the [[British Empire|Empire]].

==Early life and career==
Bengough was born on 25 November 1837, and educated at [[Rugby School]] in [[Warwickshire]] from 1851.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/rugbyschool00braduoft/rugbyschool00braduoft_djvu.txt Rugby School]</ref>

He was added to the Commander-in-Chief<U+2019>s list of potential officers in February 1853, aged barely 16. He was [[Officer (armed forces)|commissioned]] [[ensign (rank)|ensign]] by [[Sale of commissions|purchase]] in the [[77th Regiment of Foot]] on 22 March 1855,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=21682|startpage=1179|date=23 March 1855|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref> and promoted [[first lieutenant|lieutenant]] on 3 October of the same year.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=21812|startpage=4131|date=9 November 1855|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref>  He achieved his [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captaincy]] by purchase on 30 December 1864.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=22925|startpage=6806|date=30 December 1864|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref> He was granted a [[Brevet (military)|brevet]] [[major (United Kingdom)|majority]] on 1 October 1877<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=24508|startpage=5462|endpage=5463|date=2 October 1877|accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref> which was made substantive on 2 February 1878.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=24561|startpage=1945|date=12 March 1878|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref>

Bengough was versed in languages and used that skill to produced a booklet on the [[Zulu language]] just before he left England.<ref name="Commandants">{{cite paper|first=Keith I.|last=Smith|author=|title=The Commandants: The Leadership of the Natal Native Contingent in the Anglo-Zulu War|version=Thesis|publisher=University of Western Australia|date=October 2005
|url=http://theses.library.uwa.edu.au/adt-WU2006.0003/|format=PDF}}</ref> The booklet was made available in the Colony.<ref name="Commandants"/> And, even though the booklet was not officially required,<ref name="Commandants"/> it still received publicity through a mention in the local press and in the General Orders.<ref name="Commandants"/> Towards the end of the [[Crimean War]], Bengough entered that war.<ref name="Commandants"/> Bengough also served in [[Australia]] and [[India]].<ref name="Commandants"/>

==The Anglo-Zulu Wars==

Lt-Col Bengough arrived in Natal with the 77th Foot in December 1878. He was placed in command of the 2nd Battalion [[Natal Native Contingent]], which formed part of [[Anthony Durnford|Durnford]]<U+2019>s [http://www.rorkesdriftvc.com/isandhlwana/durnford.htm] [[Column (formation)|Column]], and which was left to protect the frontier at [[Kranskop|Kranz Kop]] on the departure of that force to join [[John Plumptre Carr Glyn|Glyn]]<U+2019>s Column.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=24699|startpage=2369|endpage=2370|date=21 March 1879|accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref> He crossed the Buffalo River in command of the battalion on 22 January 1879. On receipt of the news of the disaster at [[Battle of Isandlwana|Isandlwana]], he hastened towards [[Rorke's Drift]], intending to join the General<U+2019>s force. En route, he received orders to proceed to Helpmakaar near [[Dundee, KwaZulu-Natal]]. Bengough was ordered to Umsinga, where, despite the desertion of large numbers of his men, he constructed Fort Bengough. He joined the division of General Edward Newdigate in May, in command of the battalion of which the numbers had increased and the discipline improved. He and the battalion took part in the advance into Zululand. He commanded the headquarters and three companies which were present at the [[Battle of Ulundi]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bengough|first=Harcourt Mortimer|date=February 27, 2002|title=Memories of a Soldier's Life|pages=124|publisher=Adamant Media Corporation|isbn=1-4021-9252-5|accessdate=13 December 2008|url=http://books.google.com/?id=bAtmQV1U1xgC&pg=PA124&dq=Harcourt+Mortimer+Bengough+Ulundi}}</ref> Bengough was [[Mentioned in Despatches]] by General Newdigate on 6 July 1879, who reported the good service rendered by the battalion in scouting and outpost duties during the action.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=24754|startpage=5105|endpage=5106|date=21 August 1879|accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref> Bengough then served in command of the battalion in [[Baker Russell|Russell]]<U+2019>s Column until the capture of the King [[Cetshwayo kaMpande|Cetewayo]], when it was disbanded.<ref>[http://www.ecomallbiz.com/easy67/generalstaff/ The Anglo Zulu War Historical Society]</ref>

Bengough visited the [[kraal]] near where the [[Prince Imperial]] was killed and recalled that he 'brought away as a memento of the sad event a [[Knobkierrie|knobkerry stick]], which I found in the kraal, and which now hangs in the hall of my house.' In the wake of a famous battle, especially one that marked the culmination of a war such as Ulundi on 4 July 1879, every European involved in the battle appeared to want to own an object that could serve as a reminder of the event.<ref>[http://www.michaelstevenson.com/africanart/essay.htm Michael Stevenson Art: Weapons Essay]</ref>

==Later career==

In common with a number of other officers after the [[Anglo-Zulu War]], Major Bengough was promoted to brevet [[Lieutenant Colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant colonel]] on 29 November 1879,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=24787|startpage=6940|date=28 November 1879|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref> he returned to regimental duty on 21 June 1880,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=24861|startpage=3807|date=6 July 1880|accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref> and he received substantive promotion to that rank on 1 July 1881.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=24999|startpage=3677|endpage=3685|date=26 July 1881|accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref> He was on half-pay for a period commencing on 29 April 1882, when he was appointed [[Adjutant-General|Assistant Adjutant General]] at [[Madras]].<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=25128|startpage=3346|date=18 July 1882|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref><ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=25142|startpage=4013|date=29 August 1882|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref> and was promoted [[colonel (United Kingdom)|colonel]] on the 29 November 1883.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=25297|startpage=6523|date=18 December 1883|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref>  He took part in the [[Third Anglo-Burmese War]], and was [[Mentioned in Despatches]] on 26 March 1886.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=25599|startpage=2972|endpage=2973|date=18 December 1883|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref>  He was given command of a Brigade in the [[Madras Army]] on 8 November 1886,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=25668|startpage=466|date=28 January 1887|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref> and was appointed a [[Companion of the Order of the Bath]] (CB) on 26 November 1886.<ref name="LondonGazette">{{LondonGazette|issue=28151|startpage=4641|date=23 June 1908|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref>  He relinquished command of the brigade on 13 November 1891.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=26228|startpage=6651|date=1 December 1891|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref>  He was appointed local major general, when he went to Jamaica on 25 October 1893.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=26452|startpage=5955|date=24 October 1893|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref> The rank was made permanent on 13 February 1894,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=26492|startpage=1372|date=6 March 1894|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref> and he relinquished the Jamaica command on 19 December 1894.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=26585|startpage=7|date=1 January 1895|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref>

His last command was of the 1st Infantry Brigade of the Aldershot Division with the rank of major general, he relinquished command on 1 December 1897.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=26917|startpage=7349|date=7 December 1897|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref>  He retired from the service on 29 November 1898;<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=27026|startpage=7393|date=25 November 1898|accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref> Bengough himself says that he did so "a little before the Boer War of 1899".<ref>Bengough, HM, ''Memories of a Soldiers Life'', Edward Arnold: London, 1913. p.213</ref>  He was promoted [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] (KCB) on 26 June 1908.<ref name="LondonGazette" />  He died in West Bognor on 20 March 1922.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Deaths |section=Deaths |day_of_week=Saturday  |date=1 April 1922 |page_number= 1 |issue=42995 |column=A}}</ref>

