==Interest in sport==

Whilst commanding the 1st Infantry Brigade in Aldershot in the 1890s he expressed the opinion that: "There can be no better pastime for soldiers than football, combining as it does skill, judgment, pluck. resource, activity &mdash; all soldierly qualities &mdash; and affording amusement to all, from the recruit enjoying the humble punt-about on the parade groundto the crowds of enthusiasts keenly watching a hard contested struggle for the final ties for the Army Cup."<ref>{{cite paper  | first = JD  | last =  Campbell  | author =   | authorlink =   | title = The Army Isn<U+2019>t All work. Physical Culture in the Evolution of the British Army, 1860 &ndash; 1920  | version = Thesis  | publisher = University of Maine  | date = December 2003  | url = http://www.library.umaine.edu/theses/pdf/CampbellJD2003.pdf  | format = PDF  | accessdate =}}</ref>

In his memoirs he gives an interesting account of his adventures in the realm of sport &mdash; [[Boar hunting|pig-sticking]], [[Tiger hunting|tiger-shooting]], and pursuing other forms of game in India and elsewhere.

